{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"Bootstrap Spacing Utilities","slug":"bootstrap-spacing-utilities","subject":"Bootstrap","category":"Frontend Framework","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"12 mins","prerequisites":["Bootstrap Utilities Overview"],"learning_objectives":["Margin vs Padding","Responsive Spacing","Auto margins"],"theory":"## Mastering White Space\nAs covered briefly before, spacing is key. Now we look at responsive and auto spacing.\n\n### Responsive Format\n`{property}{sides}-{breakpoint}-{size}`\nExample: `mt-md-5` (Margin Top is 5 ONLY on Medium and up. On small screens, it's 0 or default).\n\n### Auto Margins\n`m-auto` centers a block. `me-auto` (margin-end: auto) pushes siblings to the right (Flexbox magic).","syntax":"class=\"px-3 py-md-5\"","examples":[{"code":"<div class=\"d-flex\">\n  <div class=\"me-auto\">Left</div>\n  <div>Right</div>\n</div>","output":"Left item on far left, Right item on far right.","explanation":"me-auto pushes the right item away."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using `mx-auto` on non-block items.","correction":"Margins only center BLOCK elements (or flex items). Span/Inline elements ignore it.","example":"<span>mx-auto</span> (Fails)"}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What specifically is `gap-3`?","answer":"It uses the CSS `gap` property (for flexbox/grid), creating space BETWEEN items, but not on the outside edges.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Create a container with 1rem padding on mobile, but 3rem padding on desktop.","hint":"p-3 p-lg-5","solution":"<div class=\"p-3 p-lg-5\">...</div>"}],"real_world_use_cases":[],"exam_notes":["Use auto margins for alignment in flexbox.","Gap is preferred over margin for lists of items."],"summary":"Responsive spacing allows your layout's density to adapt to screen size (tight on mobile, spacious on web).","order":31},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"bootstrap-introduction","path":"content/bootstrap/bootstrap-introduction.json","title":"Intr